The `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` error means you've exceeded either your queries-per-second (QPS) or daily quota limit for a given API. This can happen during traffic spikes or if your application is making too many rapid requests without throttling.

There are a few ways to resolve it:

1. **Implement exponential backoff** — retry failed requests with increasing delays
2. **Batch requests** where possible to reduce total call volume
3. **Check your quota** in Cloud Console > APIs & Services > Quotas
4. **Request a quota increase** if your legitimate usage consistently exceeds the limit

Here's a retry implementation with exponential backoff:

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Wait 1s, then 2s, then 4s before each retry
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000));
        continue;
      }
      throw error;
    }
  }
}
```

Also worth noting: if you're using the Places Autocomplete API, make sure you're using **session tokens**. Without them, every keystroke is billed as a separate request, which can burn through your quota quickly and also drive up costs [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

Use the new **`PlaceAutocompleteElement`** (web component) or the updated `Autocomplete` widget backed by the Places API (New). The legacy `PlacesService`-based approach is being actively replaced, and the new APIs offer better billing efficiency through required field masking, native Promise support, and improved session token handling [Source 2, Source 3].

Here's a comparison of the two approaches:

**Legacy (not recommended):**
```javascript
// Callback-based, less cost control
const service = new google.maps.places.PlacesService(map);
service.getDetails(
  { placeId: "ChIJ...", fields: ["name", "geometry"] },
  (place, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.places.PlacesServiceStatus.OK) {
      console.log(place.name);
    }
  }
);
```

**New — `PlaceAutocompleteElement` (recommended):**
```javascript
// Modern web component approach
const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
  componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
});

document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
  const place = event.place;
  // Only request fields you actually need — you only pay for what you request
  await place.fetchFields({ fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"] });
  console.log(place.displayName);
});
```

**New — `Autocomplete` widget (also recommended if you need more control):**
```javascript
const { Autocomplete } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const autocomplete = new Autocomplete(
  document.getElementById("search-input"),
  {
    types: ["geocode", "establishment"],
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
    fields: ["place_id", "geometry", "formatted_address", "name"],
  }
);

autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", () => {
  const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
  if (!place.geometry) {
    console.error("No geometry returned for selected place");
    return;
  }
  map.setCenter(place.geometry.location);
  map.setZoom(15);
});
```

**One critical billing note**: Always use **session tokens** with autocomplete. Without them, every keystroke the user types is billed as a separate Autocomplete request. With a session token, the entire autocomplete interaction plus the subsequent Place Details call is grouped into a single billed session — significantly cheaper [Source 5].

```javascript
const sessionToken = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteSessionToken();

const service = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteService();
service.getPlacePredictions(
  { input: userInput, sessionToken },
  (predictions) => { /* handle predictions */ }
);
```

The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` handles session tokens automatically for you, which is another reason to prefer it [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)
